l landed elites.</p></note></ref><ref id="b170-80.1chakrabarti"><label>170.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Irschik</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Dialogue and History</italic></source> (n. 160), pp. <fpage>48</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>50</lpage></citation></ref><ref id="b171-80.1chakrabarti"><label>171.</label><citation citation-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Susan</surname><given-names>Neild-Basu</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;The Dubashes of Madras,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Mod. Asian Studies</italic></source>, <year>1984</year>, <volume>18</volume>: <fpage>1</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>31</lpage>, <comment>on p. 4.</comment></citation></ref><ref id="b172-80.1chakrabarti"><label>172.</label><note><p>As part of the general investigations of corruption in India instituted by the House of Commons after the 1773 Regulation Act, Charles Newman was sent as investigating commissioner to Madras to inquire into some specific allegations against Governor Sir Thomas Rumboldt (1778&#x02013;80): <citation citation-type="other" id="N0x2431540N0x3ebfcc0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Arasaratnam</surname></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Trade and Political Dominion&#x0201d;</article-title> (n. 166), p. <fpage>24</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b173-80.1chakrabarti"><label>173.</label><citation citation-type="other"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Arasaratnam</surname></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Trade and Political Dominion&#x0201d;</article-title> (n. 166), p. <fpage>17</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>18</lpage></citation></ref><ref id="b174-80.1chakrabarti"><label>174.</label><note><p>Public dispatches from England, 13 March 1761, para. 101, p. 228, E/4/862, OIOC (emphasis added). It must be added here that the entire military establishment seems to have suffered from poor wages during these years of confict. During the war of 1780, the English Company had funded its army poorly; often the pay of the troops was twelve months in arrears: <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3ebffc0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Irschik</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Dialogue and History</italic></source> (n. 160), pp. <fpage>15</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>16</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b175-80.1chakrabarti"><label>175.</label><note><p>14 October 1765, Madras Public Consultations (n. 5), P/240/23, p. 494.</p></note></ref><ref id="b176-80.1chakrabarti"><label>176.</label><citation citation-type="book"><collab>Medical Board</collab>, <day>29</day><month>3</month><year>1802</year>, <source>SGR</source>, vol. <volume>13</volume><comment>(n. 50), p. 62</comment></citation></ref><ref id="b177-80.1chakrabarti"><label>177.</label><note><p>Proceedings, <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3ec02c0"><collab>Medical Board</collab>, <day>03</day><month>7</month><year>1802</year>, <source>SGR</source>, p. <fpage>169</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b178-80.1chakrabarti"><label>178.</label><note><p>For example, the Madras Hospital Board was obliged to try out Ruspine's Styptic Solution, which was sent to Fort St. George to be experimented upon, and injunctions were sent to the surgeons for a &#x0201c;fair trial&#x0201d;: <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3ec03e0"><collab>Fort St. George</collab>, <article-title>Extract of General Letters from England</article-title><day>22</day><month>12</month><year>1786</year>, 26 May 1787, para. 13, <source>SGR</source>, vol. <volume>1</volume> (n. 24), p. <fpage>66</fpage></citation> Also see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3ec04a0"><source>SGR</source><source>SGR</source>, p. <fpage>114</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b179-80.1chakrabarti"><label>179.</label><note><p>See, e.g., <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3ec0560"><source>SGR</source>, vol. <volume>14</volume> (5 January 1803 to 27 December 1803), G. 12451, pp. <fpage>23</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>24</lpage></citation> Also see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x3ec05c0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Niels</surname><given-names>Brimnes</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Variolation, Vaccination and Popular Resistance in Early Colonial South India,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Med. Hist</italic></source>, <year>2004</year>, <volume>48</volume>: <fpage>199</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>228</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">15151104</pub-id></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b180-80.1chakrabarti"><label>180.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Hunting</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>History</italic></source> (n. 108), p. <fpage>173</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b181-80.1chakrabarti"><label>181.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Hunting</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>History</italic></source> (n. 108), p. <fpage>173</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b182-80.1chakrabarti"><label>182.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Thomas</surname><given-names>Champney</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Medical and Chirurgical Reform Proposed, from a Review of the Healing Art, Throughout Europe, Particularly Great Britain</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>London</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Johnson</publisher-name>, <year>1797</year>).</citation></ref><ref id="b183-80.1chakrabarti"><label>183.</label><citation citation-type="book"><collab>Medical Board, Fort St. George</collab>, <day>13</day><month>10</month><year>1800</year>, <source>SGR</source>, vol. <volume>12</volume> (n. 72), p. <fpage>103</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b184-80.1chakrabarti"><label>184.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3ec0ce0"><collab>Medical Board, Fort St. George</collab>, <day>13</day><month>10</month><year>1800</year>, <source>SGR</source>, vol. <volume>12</volume>, p. <fpage>106</fpage></citation> The Board was also scathing about the profit motives: &#x0201c;That considerable private emolument might from such a source accrue, we have no manner to doubt, but we are of opinion that, it would be more commendable in Gentlemen having such speculations in view, to avoid the Service altogether; and rather endeavour to obtain the permission of the Government to settle in the Country as private adventurers&#x0201d; (<citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3ec0da0"><collab>Medical Board, Fort St. George</collab>, <day>13</day><month>10</month><year>1800</year>, <source>SGR</source>, vol. <volume>12</volume>, p. <fpage>106</fpage></citation>).</p></note></ref><ref id="b185-80.1chakrabarti"><label>185.</label><citation citation-type="book"><collab>Medical Board, Fort St. George</collab>, <day>13</day><month>10</month><year>1800</year>, <source>SGR</source>, vol. <volume>12</volume>, p. <fpage>106</fpage><comment>(emphasis added)</comment></citation></ref><ref id="b186-80.1chakrabarti"><label>186.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3ec0fe0"><collab>Medical Board, Fort St. George</collab>, <day>13</day><month>10</month><year>1800</year>, <source>SGR</source>, vol. <volume>12</volume>, p. <fpage>106</fpage><comment>(emphasis added)</comment></citation> This was part of Governor Campbell's initiative in cleaning up the administration and checking &#x0201c;clandestine&#x0201d; trading activities and &#x0201c;private concerns&#x0201d; of army officers and civil servants. The new governor found that the embezzlement of military stores at Madras had been going on for forty years: see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3ec10a0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Furber</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>John Company at Work</italic></source> (n. 64), p. <fpage>200</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b187-80.1chakrabarti"><label>187.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Edward John</surname><given-names>Waring</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Remarks on the Uses of Some of the Bazaar Medicines and Common Medical Plants of India, with a Full Index of Diseases, Indicating Their Treatment by These and Other Agents Procurable throughout India. To Which Added Directions for Treatment in Cases of Drowning, Snake-bites, &#x00026;c.</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>London</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Churchill</publisher-name>, <year>1875</year>), pp. <fpage>xi</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>xii</lpage></citation></ref><ref id="b188-80.1chakrabarti"><label>188.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x20644f0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Rajat Kanta</surname><given-names>Ray</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Asian Capital in the Age of European Domination: The Rise of the Bazaar, 1800&#x02013;1914,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Mod. Asian Studies</italic></source>, <year>1995</year>, <volume>29</volume>: <fpage>449</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>554</lpage>,  <comment>on p. 551</comment></citation> Also see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x2064610"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Anand A.</surname><given-names>Yang</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Bazaar India: Markets, Society, and the Colonial State in Gangetic Bihar</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Berkeley</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>University of California Press</publisher-name>, <year>1998</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b189-80.1chakrabarti"><label>189.</label><citation citation-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Prasannan</surname><given-names>Parthasarathi</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Rethinking Wages and Competitiveness in the Eighteenth Century: Britain and South India,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Past &#x00026; Pres.</italic></source>, <year>1998</year>, <volume>158</volume>: <fpage>79</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>109</lpage>, <comment>on p. 107</comment></citation></ref><ref id="b190-80.1chakrabarti"><label>190.</label><citation citation-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>H. M.</surname><given-names>Boot</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Real Incomes of the British Middle Class, 1760&#x02013;1850: The Experience of Clerks at the East India Company,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Econ. Hist. Rev.</italic></source>, <year>1999</year>, <volume>52</volume>: <fpage>638</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>68</lpage></citation></ref><ref id="b191-80.1chakrabarti"><label>191.</label><citation citation-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Javier Cuenca</surname><given-names>Esteban</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;The British Balance of Payments, 1772&#x02013;1820: India Transfers and War Finance,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Econ. Hist. Rev.</italic></source>, <year>2001</year>, <volume>54</volume>: <fpage>58</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>86</lpage></citation></ref></ref-list></back></article>





